<span class="poster comment-poster"><span class="comment-from-text">From:</span> <span lj:user="transitional_writes" style="white-space: nowrap;" class="ljuser"><a href="profile"><img src="https://www.dreamwidth.org/img/silk/identity/user.png" alt="[personal profile] " width="17" height="17" style="vertical-align: text-bottom; border: 0; padding-right: 1px;" /></a><a href="index.html"><b>transitional_writes</b></a></span></span>
<div class="comment-content">Here is the shortest possible introduction you can paste at the top of your Dreamwidth post (or any version of the text). It keeps only the core theorems and observations, with direct references to the well-known sources.Prerequisites (minimal)This text rests on six well-established ideas:Solomonoff induction — The optimal way to infer future behavior from observations is to assign higher probability to the shortest program (in bits) that explains the data so far.<br />(Ray Solomonoff, 1964; see Wikipedia: Solomonoff's theory of inductive inference)<br />Kolmogorov complexity — The complexity of any object (including a sequence of human actions) is the length of the shortest computer program that outputs it. Real human behavior has extremely high, largely incompressible Kolmogorov complexity.<br />(Andrey Kolmogorov, 1963; Wikipedia: Kolmogorov complexity)<br />Decentralized control — Complex coordination (e.g., the Internet) emerges from local rules without any central node holding the full map (TCP/IP packet switching is the canonical example).<br />(Standard networking; Hayek’s spontaneous order is the economic analogue)<br />Economic calculation problem — Rational allocation of scarce resources is possible for an individual (or a society) only when stable prices exist in a conserved medium of exchange. Without it, computation collapses.<br />(Ludwig von Mises, “Economic Calculation in the Socialist Commonwealth”, 1920)<br />Bounded individual complexity + inductive-inference bottleneck — Any single person has strictly limited algorithmic capacity. Person-to-person reports are always lossy projections; they cannot be fully trusted because the receiver must inductively guess the hidden “source code” behind the observed signal (replay attacks, incentives, noise).<br />Core observation — Tasks whose Kolmogorov complexity exceeds any single brain can be solved only by decentralized markets running on physically preserving / conserved money (gold, Bitcoin-as-energy, etc.). Fiat or changeable “reports” inject central rewriting rules that cap complexity and destroy reliable calculation.<br />(Synthesis of the above; cf. Elon Musk: “Bitcoin is based on energy — you can issue fake fiat currency, but it is impossible to fake energy”)<br /><br />With these six concepts alone, the rest of the argument follows directly: elementary action triangles (actor–means–ends) compose into unbounded market computation, while any central “interpreter” or regulator necessarily fails.This version is concise (under 300 words), self-contained, and points readers to the exact well-known sources. It assumes no prior Austrian or complexity background beyond the ability to click a Wikipedia link or read Mises’ short 1920 essay.You can copy-paste it verbatim. If you want an even shorter one-sentence version or a slightly expanded bullet for any point, just say so.<br /><br /></div></div>
